WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:06.040
Hello and welcome back. In this new lesson, we are going to take a look at

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:11.020
how we can use Codex for reverse engineering. This means we are not going

00:00:11.020 --> 00:00:16.840
to use OpenCLAW. Instead, we will use Codex directly to connect to the MCP

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:26.890
services. This is the Codex strategy to simulate OpenCLAW. So these are the

00:00:26.890 --> 00:00:35.770
points. First, we will prompt Codex to find out how to use MCP endpoints. Each MCP will have different

00:00:36.730 --> 00:00:44.010
endpoints. For example, the x64 debugger will have an endpoint running on a specific port.

00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:52.170
The Ghidra will have another different port number and the DNSpy will have a different port number.

00:00:52.170 --> 00:01:04.050
So each different MCP endpoints are unique. So the strategy is, we will let Codex know the port

00:01:04.050 --> 00:01:11.850
number and the IP address for the service, the MCP service that is running. And then we will

00:01:11.850 --> 00:01:21.870
tell Codex to use MCP protocol and JSON to try to connect to that endpoint. Codex might

00:01:21.870 --> 00:01:29.150
stumble and make some attempts and eventually Codex will figure it out. Now once Codex has

00:01:29.150 --> 00:01:35.470
figured out how to connect to that specific endpoint, we will then save it as a skill

00:01:36.110 --> 00:01:45.230
in a Markdown file format. This is crucial. This is what allows Codex to behave like OpenClaw.

00:01:45.230 --> 00:01:54.230
So we need to save the skill in a file and we will use the Markdown file format which

00:01:54.230 --> 00:01:56.650
OpenClaw uses.

00:01:56.650 --> 00:02:05.010
And not only that, Markdown files which have the .md extension are the default text files

00:02:05.010 --> 00:02:12.270
for all AI agents when they are saving data, knowledge, skills and memory.

00:02:12.270 --> 00:02:18.110
So they are universally accepted file format for AI agents to use.

00:02:18.110 --> 00:02:24.790
So that is the reason why we are also following this universal standard.

00:02:24.790 --> 00:02:29.870
So each skill will have its own skills markdown file.

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:37.030
So for example, if we are going to teach codex or ask codex to figure out how to

00:02:37.030 --> 00:02:42.310
connect to x64 dbg debugger, at the end of the session,

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:48.110
we will save a skill file for x64dbg debugger.

00:02:48.110 --> 00:02:51.110
And then we will repeat the process

00:02:51.110 --> 00:02:53.770
if we want Codex to learn how to connect

00:02:53.770 --> 00:02:58.370
to another different tool, for example, Ghidra.

00:02:58.370 --> 00:03:00.550
And then at the end of the Ghidra session,

00:03:00.550 --> 00:03:03.710
we will again repeat the same strategy.

00:03:03.710 --> 00:03:12.110
That is, we will ask Codex to save the Ghidra MCP connection skills in another Markdown file.

00:03:12.110 --> 00:03:17.470
And same thing repeats with DnSpy and just about any other tools.

00:03:17.470 --> 00:03:22.190
So for each specific tool, we will use the same strategy.

00:03:22.190 --> 00:03:26.910
In the end, we will have several Markdown files.

00:03:26.910 --> 00:03:30.790
Each file will be specific for a specific skill.

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:39.890
So in future, if we ever again wanted to use codex to connect to, for example, x64 debugger,

00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:43.570
then all we need to do is just refer codex to that file.

00:03:43.570 --> 00:03:46.470
So codex will just read the file.

00:03:46.470 --> 00:03:52.830
The file will tell codex how it previously managed to connect to x64 dbg debugger.

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:55.550
So it doesn't have to start from scratch.

00:03:55.550 --> 00:04:02.430
So this is the secret of how we can use Codex to simulate openclaw.

00:04:02.430 --> 00:04:07.590
And the same thing could be said for Claude code as well.

00:04:07.590 --> 00:04:14.830
If you want to use Claude code for reverse engineering, you will also do the same workflow.

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:18.190
So this is quite flexible, this strategy.

00:04:18.190 --> 00:04:23.190
It can be used for just about any AI agent that you want.

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:29.030
So in this section, I will use Codex to demonstrate the idea.

00:04:29.030 --> 00:04:31.350
So that's all for this lesson.

00:04:31.350 --> 00:04:33.050
I will see you in the next one.

00:04:33.050 --> 00:04:33.710
Thanks for watching.

